A [message|https://bitbucket.org/account/notifications/read/41569449/replacement-to-last_received-direct-message] I got starts with something like:

{code}
Lucas Sampaio sent you a message on Bitbucket:
{code}

However, when BitBucket displays my reply to that same message, it starts with:

{code}
Jurko Gospodnetić deixou uma mensagem para você no Bitbucket:
{code}

Most likely BitBucket is trying to be helpful and is localizing the same message based on the recipient&#x27;s native language, but here it only confuses me. I do not understand the language, did not write the text myself and &#x27;Jurko Gospodnetić&#x27; certainly did not send the message to &#x27;me&#x27;. :smile:

The notification seems intended for the recipient, and not something that should be displayed when I view the message or something that should be included in the message body at all.

Hope this helps.

Best regards,\\
Jurko Gospodnetić

After a team member did a commit to one of our private repositories, we are unable to browse the sources or see the latest commit. The error message we get is teh following:

{code}
#!python

Something went wrong.

You can contact support or create a public issue if the problem persists.
This might be useful in debugging the problem:
bb219e34c3664ec79599995b6bb3cac6
You can also visit our status page.
{code}

The time for when an issue is created by an anonymous user is incorrect.

There are two problems:

# The time is off by one hour
# The mouse-over time is displayed in GMT/UTC instead of local time for me (the viewer). This is inconsistent with the comments of regular users for which the time is displayed as local time.

h1. Example
See https://bitbucket.org/Manfre/django-mssql/issue/50/schema-name-needs-to-be-checked-and

h3. Anonymous user&#x27;s post time
{code}
#!html

<time datetime="2014-01-06T18:29:15.670634" title="6 January 2014 18:29">an hour ago</time>
{code}

# The post was created 12:29 PM EST (GMT-5), which means the {{datetime}} attribute should have been {{"2014-01-06T17:29:15.670634"}} or {{"2014-01-06T12:29:15.670634-05:00"}}.
# The mouse over display time should be displayed in my local time, which should have been {{"6 January 2014 12:29"}}

h3. [Regular user&#x27;s post time|https://bitbucket.org/Manfre/django-mssql/issue/50/schema-name-needs-to-be-checked-and#comment-7609098]
{code}
#!html

<time title="6 January 2014 12:59" datetime="2014-01-06T12:59:11-05:00" data-title="true">an hour ago</time>
{code}

This is correct and is exactly as expected

The incorrect time from the issue creation implies that the issue was created after the comment, which is impossible.

----
Update: The timezone issue seems to affect non-anonymous users too... see https://bitbucket.org/Manfre/django-mssql/issue/45/disabling-uses_savepoints-for-mars\\
Not sure when this issue was created though so I don&#x27;t know whether it was off by an hour too as the comment could have been posted 1hr 2 mins later.

